.SS "lenscorrection"
.IX Subsection "lenscorrection"
Correct radial lens distortion
.PP
This filter can be used to correct for radial distortion as can result from the use
of wide angle lenses, and thereby re-rectify the image. To find the right parameters
one can use tools available for example as part of opencv or simply trial-and-error.
To use opencv use the calibration sample (under samples/cpp) from the opencv sources
and extract the k1 and k2 coefficients from the resulting matrix.
.PP
Note that effectively the same filter is available in the open-source tools Krita and
Digikam from the \s-1KDE\s0 project.
.PP
In contrast to the \fBvignette\fR filter, which can also be used to compensate lens errors,
this filter corrects the distortion of the image, whereas \fBvignette\fR corrects the
brightness distribution, so you may want to use both filters together in certain
cases, though you will have to take care of ordering, i.e. whether vignetting should
be applied before or after lens correction.
.PP
\fIOptions\fR
.IX Subsection "Options"
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBcx\fR" 4
.IX Item "cx"
Relative x\-coordinate of the focal point of the image, and thereby the center of the
distortion. This value has a range [0,1] and is expressed as fractions of the image
width. Default is 0.5.
.IP "\fBcy\fR" 4
.IX Item "cy"
Relative y\-coordinate of the focal point of the image, and thereby the center of the
distortion. This value has a range [0,1] and is expressed as fractions of the image
height. Default is 0.5.
.IP "\fBk1\fR" 4
.IX Item "k1"
Coefficient of the quadratic correction term. This value has a range [\-1,1]. 0 means
no correction. Default is 0.
.IP "\fBk2\fR" 4
.IX Item "k2"
Coefficient of the double quadratic correction term. This value has a range [\-1,1].
0 means no correction. Default is 0.
.IP "\fBi\fR" 4
.IX Item "i"
Set interpolation type. Can be \f(CW\*(C`nearest\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`bilinear\*(C'\fR.
Default is \f(CW\*(C`nearest\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBfc\fR" 4
.IX Item "fc"
Specify the color of the unmapped pixels. For the syntax of this option,
check the \fB\*(L"Color\*(R" section in the ffmpeg-utils
manual\fR. Default color is \f(CW\*(C`black@0\*(C'\fR.
.PP
The formula that generates the correction is:
.PP
\&\fIr_src\fR = \fIr_tgt\fR * (1 + \fIk1\fR * (\fIr_tgt\fR / \fIr_0\fR)^2 + \fIk2\fR * (\fIr_tgt\fR / \fIr_0\fR)^4)
.PP
where \fIr_0\fR is halve of the image diagonal and \fIr_src\fR and \fIr_tgt\fR are the
distances from the focal point in the source and target images, respectively.
.PP
\fICommands\fR
.IX Subsection "Commands"
.PP
This filter supports the all above options as \fBcommands\fR.
.SS "lensfun"
.IX Subsection "lensfun"
Apply lens correction via the lensfun library (<\fBhttp://lensfun.sourceforge.net/\fR>).
.PP
The \f(CW\*(C`lensfun\*(C'\fR filter requires the camera make, camera model, and lens model
to apply the lens correction. The filter will load the lensfun database and
query it to find the corresponding camera and lens entries in the database. As
long as these entries can be found with the given options, the filter can
perform corrections on frames. Note that incomplete strings will result in the
filter choosing the best match with the given options, and the filter will
output the chosen camera and lens models (logged with level \*(L"info\*(R"). You must
provide the make, camera model, and lens model as they are required.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBmake\fR" 4
.IX Item "make"
The make of the camera (for example, \*(L"Canon\*(R"). This option is required.
.IP "\fBmodel\fR" 4
.IX Item "model"
The model of the camera (for example, \*(L"Canon \s-1EOS 100D\*(R"\s0). This option is
required.
.IP "\fBlens_model\fR" 4
.IX Item "lens_model"
The model of the lens (for example, \*(L"Canon EF-S 18\-55mm f/3.5\-5.6 \s-1IS STM\*(R"\s0). This
option is required.
.IP "\fBmode\fR" 4
.IX Item "mode"
The type of correction to apply. The following values are valid options:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBvignetting\fR" 4
.IX Item "vignetting"
Enables fixing lens vignetting.
.IP "\fBgeometry\fR" 4
.IX Item "geometry"
Enables fixing lens geometry. This is the default.
.IP "\fBsubpixel\fR" 4
.IX Item "subpixel"
Enables fixing chromatic aberrations.
.IP "\fBvig_geo\fR" 4
.IX Item "vig_geo"
Enables fixing lens vignetting and lens geometry.
.IP "\fBvig_subpixel\fR" 4
.IX Item "vig_subpixel"
Enables fixing lens vignetting and chromatic aberrations.
.IP "\fBdistortion\fR" 4
.IX Item "distortion"
Enables fixing both lens geometry and chromatic aberrations.
.IP "\fBall\fR" 4
.IX Item "all"
Enables all possible corrections.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBfocal_length\fR" 4
.IX Item "focal_length"
The focal length of the image/video (zoom; expected constant for video). For
example, a 18\-\-55mm lens has focal length range of [18\-\-55], so a value in that
range should be chosen when using that lens. Default 18.
.IP "\fBaperture\fR" 4
.IX Item "aperture"
The aperture of the image/video (expected constant for video). Note that
aperture is only used for vignetting correction. Default 3.5.
.IP "\fBfocus_distance\fR" 4
.IX Item "focus_distance"
The focus distance of the image/video (expected constant for video). Note that
focus distance is only used for vignetting and only slightly affects the
vignetting correction process. If unknown, leave it at the default value (which
is 1000).
.IP "\fBscale\fR" 4
.IX Item "scale"
The scale factor which is applied after transformation. After correction the
video is no longer necessarily rectangular. This parameter controls how much of
the resulting image is visible. The value 0 means that a value will be chosen
automatically such that there is little or no unmapped area in the output
image. 1.0 means that no additional scaling is done. Lower values may result
in more of the corrected image being visible, while higher values may avoid
unmapped areas in the output.
.IP "\fBtarget_geometry\fR" 4
.IX Item "target_geometry"
The target geometry of the output image/video. The following values are valid
options:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBrectilinear (default)\fR" 4
.IX Item "rectilinear (default)"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBfisheye\fR" 4
.IX Item "fisheye"
.IP "\fBpanoramic\fR" 4
.IX Item "panoramic"
.IP "\fBequirectangular\fR" 4
.IX Item "equirectangular"
.IP "\fBfisheye_orthographic\fR" 4
.IX Item "fisheye_orthographic"
.IP "\fBfisheye_stereographic\fR" 4
.IX Item "fisheye_stereographic"
.IP "\fBfisheye_equisolid\fR" 4
.IX Item "fisheye_equisolid"
.IP "\fBfisheye_thoby\fR" 4
.IX Item "fisheye_thoby"
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBreverse\fR" 4
.IX Item "reverse"
.PD
Apply the reverse of image correction (instead of correcting distortion, apply
it).
.IP "\fBinterpolation\fR" 4
.IX Item "interpolation"
The type of interpolation used when correcting distortion. The following values
are valid options:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBnearest\fR" 4
.IX Item "nearest"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBlinear (default)\fR" 4
.IX Item "linear (default)"
.IP "\fBlanczos\fR" 4
.IX Item "lanczos"
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.PD
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply lens correction with make \*(L"Canon\*(R", camera model \*(L"Canon \s-1EOS 100D\*(R",\s0 and lens
model \*(L"Canon EF-S 18\-55mm f/3.5\-5.6 \s-1IS STM\*(R"\s0 with focal length of \*(L"18\*(R" and
aperture of \*(L"8.0\*(R".
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-i input.mov \-vf lensfun=make=Canon:model="Canon EOS 100D":lens_model="Canon EF\-S 18\-55mm f/3.5\-5.6 IS STM":focal_length=18:aperture=8 \-c:v h264 \-b:v 8000k output.mov
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply the same as before, but only for the first 5 seconds of video.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-i input.mov \-vf lensfun=make=Canon:model="Canon EOS 100D":lens_model="Canon EF\-S 18\-55mm f/3.5\-5.6 IS STM":focal_length=18:aperture=8:enable=\*(Aqlte(t\e,5)\*(Aq \-c:v h264 \-b:v 8000k output.mov
.Ve
.SS "libvmaf"
.IX Subsection "libvmaf"
Obtain the \s-1VMAF\s0 (Video Multi-Method Assessment Fusion)
score between two input videos.
.PP
The obtained \s-1VMAF\s0 score is printed through the logging system.
.PP
It requires Netflix's vmaf library (libvmaf) as a pre-requisite.
After installing the library it can be enabled using:
\&\f(CW\*(C`./configure \-\-enable\-libvmaf\*(C'\fR.
If no model path is specified it uses the default model: \f(CW\*(C`vmaf_v0.6.1.pkl\*(C'\fR.
.PP
The filter has following options:
.IP "\fBmodel_path\fR" 4
.IX Item "model_path"
Set the model path which is to be used for \s-1SVM.\s0
Default value: \f(CW"/usr/local/share/model/vmaf_v0.6.1.pkl"\fR
.IP "\fBlog_path\fR" 4
.IX Item "log_path"
Set the file path to be used to store logs.
.IP "\fBlog_fmt\fR" 4
.IX Item "log_fmt"
Set the format of the log file (csv, json or xml).
.IP "\fBenable_transform\fR" 4
.IX Item "enable_transform"
This option can enable/disable the \f(CW\*(C`score_transform\*(C'\fR applied to the final predicted \s-1VMAF\s0 score,
if you have specified score_transform option in the input parameter file passed to \f(CW\*(C`run_vmaf_training.py\*(C'\fR
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.IP "\fBphone_model\fR" 4
.IX Item "phone_model"
Invokes the phone model which will generate \s-1VMAF\s0 scores higher than in the
regular model, which is more suitable for laptop, \s-1TV,\s0 etc. viewing conditions.
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.IP "\fBpsnr\fR" 4
.IX Item "psnr"
Enables computing psnr along with vmaf.
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.IP "\fBssim\fR" 4
.IX Item "ssim"
Enables computing ssim along with vmaf.
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.IP "\fBms_ssim\fR" 4
.IX Item "ms_ssim"
Enables computing ms_ssim along with vmaf.
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.IP "\fBpool\fR" 4
.IX Item "pool"
Set the pool method to be used for computing vmaf.
Options are \f(CW\*(C`min\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`harmonic_mean\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`mean\*(C'\fR (default).
.IP "\fBn_threads\fR" 4
.IX Item "n_threads"
Set number of threads to be used when computing vmaf.
Default value: \f(CW0\fR, which makes use of all available logical processors.
.IP "\fBn_subsample\fR" 4
.IX Item "n_subsample"
Set interval for frame subsampling used when computing vmaf.
Default value: \f(CW1\fR
.IP "\fBenable_conf_interval\fR" 4
.IX Item "enable_conf_interval"
Enables confidence interval.
Default value: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.PP
This filter also supports the \fBframesync\fR options.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
On the below examples the input file \fImain.mpg\fR being processed is
compared with the reference file \fIref.mpg\fR.
