.SS "nlmeans_opencl"
.IX Subsection "nlmeans_opencl"
Non-local Means denoise filter through OpenCL, this filter accepts same options as \fBnlmeans\fR.
.SS "overlay_opencl"
.IX Subsection "overlay_opencl"
Overlay one video on top of another.
.PP
It takes two inputs and has one output. The first input is the \*(L"main\*(R" video on which the second input is overlaid.
This filter requires same memory layout for all the inputs. So, format conversion may be needed.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBx\fR" 4
.IX Item "x"
Set the x coordinate of the overlaid video on the main video.
Default value is \f(CW0\fR.
.IP "\fBy\fR" 4
.IX Item "y"
Set the y coordinate of the overlaid video on the main video.
Default value is \f(CW0\fR.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Overlay an image \s-1LOGO\s0 at the top-left corner of the \s-1INPUT\s0 video. Both inputs are yuv420p format.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-i LOGO \-filter_complex "[0:v]hwupload[a], [1:v]format=yuv420p, hwupload[b], [a][b]overlay_opencl, hwdownload" OUTPUT
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
The inputs have same memory layout for color channels , the overlay has additional alpha plane, like \s-1INPUT\s0 is yuv420p, and the \s-1LOGO\s0 is yuva420p.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-i LOGO \-filter_complex "[0:v]hwupload[a], [1:v]format=yuva420p, hwupload[b], [a][b]overlay_opencl, hwdownload" OUTPUT
.Ve
.SS "pad_opencl"
.IX Subsection "pad_opencl"
Add paddings to the input image, and place the original input at the
provided \fIx\fR, \fIy\fR coordinates.
.PP
It accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBwidth, w\fR" 4
.IX Item "width, w"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBheight, h\fR" 4
.IX Item "height, h"
.PD
Specify an expression for the size of the output image with the
paddings added. If the value for \fIwidth\fR or \fIheight\fR is 0, the
corresponding input size is used for the output.
.Sp
The \fIwidth\fR expression can reference the value set by the
\&\fIheight\fR expression, and vice versa.
.Sp
The default value of \fIwidth\fR and \fIheight\fR is 0.
.IP "\fBx\fR" 4
.IX Item "x"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBy\fR" 4
.IX Item "y"
.PD
Specify the offsets to place the input image at within the padded area,
with respect to the top/left border of the output image.
.Sp
The \fIx\fR expression can reference the value set by the \fIy\fR
expression, and vice versa.
.Sp
The default value of \fIx\fR and \fIy\fR is 0.
.Sp
If \fIx\fR or \fIy\fR evaluate to a negative number, they'll be changed
so the input image is centered on the padded area.
.IP "\fBcolor\fR" 4
.IX Item "color"
Specify the color of the padded area. For the syntax of this option,
check the \fB\*(L"Color\*(R" section in the ffmpeg-utils
manual\fR.
.IP "\fBaspect\fR" 4
.IX Item "aspect"
Pad to an aspect instead to a resolution.
.PP
The value for the \fIwidth\fR, \fIheight\fR, \fIx\fR, and \fIy\fR
options are expressions containing the following constants:
.IP "\fBin_w\fR" 4
.IX Item "in_w"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBin_h\fR" 4
.IX Item "in_h"
.PD
The input video width and height.
.IP "\fBiw\fR" 4
.IX Item "iw"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBih\fR" 4
.IX Item "ih"
.PD
These are the same as \fIin_w\fR and \fIin_h\fR.
.IP "\fBout_w\fR" 4
.IX Item "out_w"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBout_h\fR" 4
.IX Item "out_h"
.PD
The output width and height (the size of the padded area), as
specified by the \fIwidth\fR and \fIheight\fR expressions.
.IP "\fBow\fR" 4
.IX Item "ow"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBoh\fR" 4
.IX Item "oh"
.PD
These are the same as \fIout_w\fR and \fIout_h\fR.
.IP "\fBx\fR" 4
.IX Item "x"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBy\fR" 4
.IX Item "y"
.PD
The x and y offsets as specified by the \fIx\fR and \fIy\fR
expressions, or \s-1NAN\s0 if not yet specified.
.IP "\fBa\fR" 4
.IX Item "a"
same as \fIiw\fR / \fIih\fR
.IP "\fBsar\fR" 4
.IX Item "sar"
input sample aspect ratio
.IP "\fBdar\fR" 4
.IX Item "dar"
input display aspect ratio, it is the same as (\fIiw\fR / \fIih\fR) * \fIsar\fR
.SS "prewitt_opencl"
.IX Subsection "prewitt_opencl"
Apply the Prewitt operator (<\fBhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prewitt_operator\fR>) to input video stream.
.PP
The filter accepts the following option:
.IP "\fBplanes\fR" 4
.IX Item "planes"
Set which planes to filter. Default value is \f(CW0xf\fR, by which all planes are processed.
.IP "\fBscale\fR" 4
.IX Item "scale"
Set value which will be multiplied with filtered result.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[0.0, 65535]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW1.0\fR.
.IP "\fBdelta\fR" 4
.IX Item "delta"
Set value which will be added to filtered result.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[\-65535, 65535]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW0.0\fR.
.PP
\fIExample\fR
.IX Subsection "Example"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply the Prewitt operator with scale set to 2 and delta set to 10.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-vf "hwupload, prewitt_opencl=scale=2:delta=10, hwdownload" OUTPUT
.Ve
.SS "program_opencl"
.IX Subsection "program_opencl"
Filter video using an OpenCL program.
.IP "\fBsource\fR" 4
.IX Item "source"
OpenCL program source file.
.IP "\fBkernel\fR" 4
.IX Item "kernel"
Kernel name in program.
.IP "\fBinputs\fR" 4
.IX Item "inputs"
Number of inputs to the filter.  Defaults to 1.
.IP "\fBsize, s\fR" 4
.IX Item "size, s"
Size of output frames.  Defaults to the same as the first input.
.PP
The \f(CW\*(C`program_opencl\*(C'\fR filter also supports the \fBframesync\fR options.
.PP
The program source file must contain a kernel function with the given name,
which will be run once for each plane of the output.  Each run on a plane
gets enqueued as a separate 2D global NDRange with one work-item for each
pixel to be generated.  The global \s-1ID\s0 offset for each work-item is therefore
the coordinates of a pixel in the destination image.
.PP
The kernel function needs to take the following arguments:
.IP "\(bu" 4
Destination image, \fI_\|_write_only image2d_t\fR.
.Sp
This image will become the output; the kernel should write all of it.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Frame index, \fIunsigned int\fR.
.Sp
This is a counter starting from zero and increasing by one for each frame.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Source images, \fI_\|_read_only image2d_t\fR.
.Sp
These are the most recent images on each input.  The kernel may read from
them to generate the output, but they can't be written to.
.PP
Example programs:
.IP "\(bu" 4
Copy the input to the output (output must be the same size as the input).
.Sp
.Vb 5
\&        _\|_kernel void copy(_\|_write_only image2d_t destination,
\&                           unsigned int index,
\&                           _\|_read_only  image2d_t source)
\&        {
\&            const sampler_t sampler = CLK_NORMALIZED_COORDS_FALSE;
\&        
\&            int2 location = (int2)(get_global_id(0), get_global_id(1));
\&        
\&            float4 value = read_imagef(source, sampler, location);
\&        
\&            write_imagef(destination, location, value);
\&        }
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply a simple transformation, rotating the input by an amount increasing
with the index counter.  Pixel values are linearly interpolated by the
sampler, and the output need not have the same dimensions as the input.
.Sp
.Vb 6
\&        _\|_kernel void rotate_image(_\|_write_only image2d_t dst,
\&                                   unsigned int index,
\&                                   _\|_read_only  image2d_t src)
\&        {
\&            const sampler_t sampler = (CLK_NORMALIZED_COORDS_FALSE |
\&                                       CLK_FILTER_LINEAR);
\&        
\&            float angle = (float)index / 100.0f;
\&        
\&            float2 dst_dim = convert_float2(get_image_dim(dst));
\&            float2 src_dim = convert_float2(get_image_dim(src));
\&        
\&            float2 dst_cen = dst_dim / 2.0f;
\&            float2 src_cen = src_dim / 2.0f;
\&        
\&            int2   dst_loc = (int2)(get_global_id(0), get_global_id(1));
\&        
\&            float2 dst_pos = convert_float2(dst_loc) \- dst_cen;
\&            float2 src_pos = {
\&                cos(angle) * dst_pos.x \- sin(angle) * dst_pos.y,
\&                sin(angle) * dst_pos.x + cos(angle) * dst_pos.y
\&            };
\&            src_pos = src_pos * src_dim / dst_dim;
\&        
\&            float2 src_loc = src_pos + src_cen;
\&        
\&            if (src_loc.x < 0.0f      || src_loc.y < 0.0f ||
\&                src_loc.x > src_dim.x || src_loc.y > src_dim.y)
\&                write_imagef(dst, dst_loc, 0.5f);
\&            else
\&                write_imagef(dst, dst_loc, read_imagef(src, sampler, src_loc));
\&        }
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Blend two inputs together, with the amount of each input used varying
with the index counter.
.Sp
.Vb 7
\&        _\|_kernel void blend_images(_\|_write_only image2d_t dst,
\&                                   unsigned int index,
\&                                   _\|_read_only  image2d_t src1,
\&                                   _\|_read_only  image2d_t src2)
\&        {
\&            const sampler_t sampler = (CLK_NORMALIZED_COORDS_FALSE |
\&                                       CLK_FILTER_LINEAR);
\&        
\&            float blend = (cos((float)index / 50.0f) + 1.0f) / 2.0f;
\&        
\&            int2  dst_loc = (int2)(get_global_id(0), get_global_id(1));
\&            int2 src1_loc = dst_loc * get_image_dim(src1) / get_image_dim(dst);
\&            int2 src2_loc = dst_loc * get_image_dim(src2) / get_image_dim(dst);
\&        
\&            float4 val1 = read_imagef(src1, sampler, src1_loc);
\&            float4 val2 = read_imagef(src2, sampler, src2_loc);
\&        
\&            write_imagef(dst, dst_loc, val1 * blend + val2 * (1.0f \- blend));
\&        }
.Ve
