.SS "tonemap_opencl"
.IX Subsection "tonemap_opencl"
Perform \s-1HDR\s0(\s-1PQ/HLG\s0) to \s-1SDR\s0 conversion with tone-mapping.
.PP
It accepts the following parameters:
.IP "\fBtonemap\fR" 4
.IX Item "tonemap"
Specify the tone-mapping operator to be used. Same as tonemap option in \fBtonemap\fR.
.IP "\fBparam\fR" 4
.IX Item "param"
Tune the tone mapping algorithm. same as param option in \fBtonemap\fR.
.IP "\fBdesat\fR" 4
.IX Item "desat"
Apply desaturation for highlights that exceed this level of brightness. The
higher the parameter, the more color information will be preserved. This
setting helps prevent unnaturally blown-out colors for super-highlights, by
(smoothly) turning into white instead. This makes images feel more natural,
at the cost of reducing information about out-of-range colors.
.Sp
The default value is 0.5, and the algorithm here is a little different from
the cpu version tonemap currently. A setting of 0.0 disables this option.
.IP "\fBthreshold\fR" 4
.IX Item "threshold"
The tonemapping algorithm parameters is fine-tuned per each scene. And a threshold
is used to detect whether the scene has changed or not. If the distance between
the current frame average brightness and the current running average exceeds
a threshold value, we would re-calculate scene average and peak brightness.
The default value is 0.2.
.IP "\fBformat\fR" 4
.IX Item "format"
Specify the output pixel format.
.Sp
Currently supported formats are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fIp010\fR" 4
.IX Item "p010"
.PD 0
.IP "\fInv12\fR" 4
.IX Item "nv12"
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBrange, r\fR" 4
.IX Item "range, r"
.PD
Set the output color range.
.Sp
Possible values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fItv/mpeg\fR" 4
.IX Item "tv/mpeg"
.PD 0
.IP "\fIpc/jpeg\fR" 4
.IX Item "pc/jpeg"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is same as input.
.RE
.IP "\fBprimaries, p\fR" 4
.IX Item "primaries, p"
Set the output color primaries.
.Sp
Possible values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fIbt709\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt709"
.PD 0
.IP "\fIbt2020\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt2020"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is same as input.
.RE
.IP "\fBtransfer, t\fR" 4
.IX Item "transfer, t"
Set the output transfer characteristics.
.Sp
Possible values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fIbt709\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt709"
.PD 0
.IP "\fIbt2020\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt2020"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is bt709.
.RE
.IP "\fBmatrix, m\fR" 4
.IX Item "matrix, m"
Set the output colorspace matrix.
.Sp
Possible value are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fIbt709\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt709"
.PD 0
.IP "\fIbt2020\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt2020"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is same as input.
.RE
.PP
\fIExample\fR
.IX Subsection "Example"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Convert \s-1HDR\s0(\s-1PQ/HLG\s0) video to bt2020\-transfer\-characteristic p010 format using linear operator.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-vf "format=p010,hwupload,tonemap_opencl=t=bt2020:tonemap=linear:format=p010,hwdownload,format=p010" OUTPUT
.Ve
.SS "unsharp_opencl"
.IX Subsection "unsharp_opencl"
Sharpen or blur the input video.
.PP
It accepts the following parameters:
.IP "\fBluma_msize_x, lx\fR" 4
.IX Item "luma_msize_x, lx"
Set the luma matrix horizontal size.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 23]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW5\fR.
.IP "\fBluma_msize_y, ly\fR" 4
.IX Item "luma_msize_y, ly"
Set the luma matrix vertical size.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 23]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW5\fR.
.IP "\fBluma_amount, la\fR" 4
.IX Item "luma_amount, la"
Set the luma effect strength.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[\-10, 10]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW1.0\fR.
.Sp
Negative values will blur the input video, while positive values will
sharpen it, a value of zero will disable the effect.
.IP "\fBchroma_msize_x, cx\fR" 4
.IX Item "chroma_msize_x, cx"
Set the chroma matrix horizontal size.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 23]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW5\fR.
.IP "\fBchroma_msize_y, cy\fR" 4
.IX Item "chroma_msize_y, cy"
Set the chroma matrix vertical size.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 23]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW5\fR.
.IP "\fBchroma_amount, ca\fR" 4
.IX Item "chroma_amount, ca"
Set the chroma effect strength.
Range is \f(CW\*(C`[\-10, 10]\*(C'\fR and default value is \f(CW0.0\fR.
.Sp
Negative values will blur the input video, while positive values will
sharpen it, a value of zero will disable the effect.
.PP
All parameters are optional and default to the equivalent of the
string '5:5:1.0:5:5:0.0'.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply strong luma sharpen effect:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-vf "hwupload, unsharp_opencl=luma_msize_x=7:luma_msize_y=7:luma_amount=2.5, hwdownload" OUTPUT
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply a strong blur of both luma and chroma parameters:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        \-i INPUT \-vf "hwupload, unsharp_opencl=7:7:\-2:7:7:\-2, hwdownload" OUTPUT
.Ve
.SS "xfade_opencl"
.IX Subsection "xfade_opencl"
Cross fade two videos with custom transition effect by using OpenCL.
.PP
It accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBtransition\fR" 4
.IX Item "transition"
Set one of possible transition effects.
.RS 4
.IP "\fBcustom\fR" 4
.IX Item "custom"
Select custom transition effect, the actual transition description
will be picked from source and kernel options.
.IP "\fBfade\fR" 4
.IX Item "fade"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBwipeleft\fR" 4
.IX Item "wipeleft"
.IP "\fBwiperight\fR" 4
.IX Item "wiperight"
.IP "\fBwipeup\fR" 4
.IX Item "wipeup"
.IP "\fBwipedown\fR" 4
.IX Item "wipedown"
.IP "\fBslideleft\fR" 4
.IX Item "slideleft"
.IP "\fBslideright\fR" 4
.IX Item "slideright"
.IP "\fBslideup\fR" 4
.IX Item "slideup"
.IP "\fBslidedown\fR" 4
.IX Item "slidedown"
.PD
Default transition is fade.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBsource\fR" 4
.IX Item "source"
OpenCL program source file for custom transition.
.IP "\fBkernel\fR" 4
.IX Item "kernel"
Set name of kernel to use for custom transition from program source file.
.IP "\fBduration\fR" 4
.IX Item "duration"
Set duration of video transition.
.IP "\fBoffset\fR" 4
.IX Item "offset"
Set time of start of transition relative to first video.
.PP
The program source file must contain a kernel function with the given name,
which will be run once for each plane of the output.  Each run on a plane
gets enqueued as a separate 2D global NDRange with one work-item for each
pixel to be generated.  The global \s-1ID\s0 offset for each work-item is therefore
the coordinates of a pixel in the destination image.
.PP
The kernel function needs to take the following arguments:
.IP "\(bu" 4
Destination image, \fI_\|_write_only image2d_t\fR.
.Sp
This image will become the output; the kernel should write all of it.
.IP "\(bu" 4
First Source image, \fI_\|_read_only image2d_t\fR.
Second Source image, \fI_\|_read_only image2d_t\fR.
.Sp
These are the most recent images on each input.  The kernel may read from
them to generate the output, but they can't be written to.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Transition progress, \fIfloat\fR. This value is always between 0 and 1 inclusive.
.PP
Example programs:
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply dots curtain transition effect:
.Sp
.Vb 11
\&        _\|_kernel void blend_images(_\|_write_only image2d_t dst,
\&                                   _\|_read_only  image2d_t src1,
\&                                   _\|_read_only  image2d_t src2,
\&                                   float progress)
\&        {
\&            const sampler_t sampler = (CLK_NORMALIZED_COORDS_FALSE |
\&                                       CLK_FILTER_LINEAR);
\&            int2  p = (int2)(get_global_id(0), get_global_id(1));
\&            float2 rp = (float2)(get_global_id(0), get_global_id(1));
\&            float2 dim = (float2)(get_image_dim(src1).x, get_image_dim(src1).y);
\&            rp = rp / dim;
\&        
\&            float2 dots = (float2)(20.0, 20.0);
\&            float2 center = (float2)(0,0);
\&            float2 unused;
\&        
\&            float4 val1 = read_imagef(src1, sampler, p);
\&            float4 val2 = read_imagef(src2, sampler, p);
\&            bool next = distance(fract(rp * dots, &unused), (float2)(0.5, 0.5)) < (progress / distance(rp, center));
\&        
\&            write_imagef(dst, p, next ? val1 : val2);
\&        }
.Ve
.SH "VAAPI VIDEO FILTERS"
.IX Header "VAAPI VIDEO FILTERS"
\&\s-1VAAPI\s0 Video filters are usually used with \s-1VAAPI\s0 decoder and \s-1VAAPI\s0 encoder. Below is a description of \s-1VAAPI\s0 video filters.
.PP
To enable compilation of these filters you need to configure FFmpeg with
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-enable\-vaapi\*(C'\fR.
.PP
To use vaapi filters, you need to setup the vaapi device correctly. For more information, please read <\fBhttps://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/Hardware/VAAPI\fR>
.SS "tonemap_vaapi"
