.Ve
.SS "concat"
.IX Subsection "concat"
Concatenate audio and video streams, joining them together one after the
other.
.PP
The filter works on segments of synchronized video and audio streams. All
segments must have the same number of streams of each type, and that will
also be the number of streams at output.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBn\fR" 4
.IX Item "n"
Set the number of segments. Default is 2.
.IP "\fBv\fR" 4
.IX Item "v"
Set the number of output video streams, that is also the number of video
streams in each segment. Default is 1.
.IP "\fBa\fR" 4
.IX Item "a"
Set the number of output audio streams, that is also the number of audio
streams in each segment. Default is 0.
.IP "\fBunsafe\fR" 4
.IX Item "unsafe"
Activate unsafe mode: do not fail if segments have a different format.
.PP
The filter has \fIv\fR+\fIa\fR outputs: first \fIv\fR video outputs, then
\&\fIa\fR audio outputs.
.PP
There are \fIn\fRx(\fIv\fR+\fIa\fR) inputs: first the inputs for the first
segment, in the same order as the outputs, then the inputs for the second
segment, etc.
.PP
Related streams do not always have exactly the same duration, for various
reasons including codec frame size or sloppy authoring. For that reason,
related synchronized streams (e.g. a video and its audio track) should be
concatenated at once. The concat filter will use the duration of the longest
stream in each segment (except the last one), and if necessary pad shorter
audio streams with silence.
.PP
For this filter to work correctly, all segments must start at timestamp 0.
.PP
All corresponding streams must have the same parameters in all segments; the
filtering system will automatically select a common pixel format for video
streams, and a common sample format, sample rate and channel layout for
audio streams, but other settings, such as resolution, must be converted
explicitly by the user.
.PP
Different frame rates are acceptable but will result in variable frame rate
at output; be sure to configure the output file to handle it.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Concatenate an opening, an episode and an ending, all in bilingual version
(video in stream 0, audio in streams 1 and 2):
.Sp
.Vb 4
\&        ffmpeg \-i opening.mkv \-i episode.mkv \-i ending.mkv \-filter_complex \e
\&          \*(Aq[0:0] [0:1] [0:2] [1:0] [1:1] [1:2] [2:0] [2:1] [2:2]
\&           concat=n=3:v=1:a=2 [v] [a1] [a2]\*(Aq \e
\&          \-map \*(Aq[v]\*(Aq \-map \*(Aq[a1]\*(Aq \-map \*(Aq[a2]\*(Aq output.mkv
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Concatenate two parts, handling audio and video separately, using the
(a)movie sources, and adjusting the resolution:
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        movie=part1.mp4, scale=512:288 [v1] ; amovie=part1.mp4 [a1] ;
\&        movie=part2.mp4, scale=512:288 [v2] ; amovie=part2.mp4 [a2] ;
\&        [v1] [v2] concat [outv] ; [a1] [a2] concat=v=0:a=1 [outa]
.Ve
.Sp
Note that a desync will happen at the stitch if the audio and video streams
do not have exactly the same duration in the first file.
.PP
\fICommands\fR
.IX Subsection "Commands"
.PP
This filter supports the following commands:
.IP "\fBnext\fR" 4
.IX Item "next"
Close the current segment and step to the next one
.SS "ebur128"
.IX Subsection "ebur128"
\&\s-1EBU R128\s0 scanner filter. This filter takes an audio stream and analyzes its loudness
level. By default, it logs a message at a frequency of 10Hz with the
Momentary loudness (identified by \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR), Short-term loudness (\f(CW\*(C`S\*(C'\fR),
Integrated loudness (\f(CW\*(C`I\*(C'\fR) and Loudness Range (\f(CW\*(C`LRA\*(C'\fR).
.PP
The filter can only analyze streams which have a sampling rate of 48000 Hz and whose
sample format is double-precision floating point. The input stream will be converted to
this specification, if needed. Users may need to insert aformat and/or aresample filters
after this filter to obtain the original parameters.
.PP
The filter also has a video output (see the \fIvideo\fR option) with a real
time graph to observe the loudness evolution. The graphic contains the logged
message mentioned above, so it is not printed anymore when this option is set,
unless the verbose logging is set. The main graphing area contains the
short-term loudness (3 seconds of analysis), and the gauge on the right is for
the momentary loudness (400 milliseconds), but can optionally be configured
to instead display short-term loudness (see \fIgauge\fR).
.PP
The green area marks a  +/\- 1LU target range around the target loudness
(\-23LUFS by default, unless modified through \fItarget\fR).
.PP
More information about the Loudness Recommendation \s-1EBU R128\s0 on
<\fBhttp://tech.ebu.ch/loudness\fR>.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBvideo\fR" 4
.IX Item "video"
Activate the video output. The audio stream is passed unchanged whether this
option is set or no. The video stream will be the first output stream if
activated. Default is \f(CW0\fR.
.IP "\fBsize\fR" 4
.IX Item "size"
Set the video size. This option is for video only. For the syntax of this
option, check the
\&\fB\*(L"Video size\*(R" section in the ffmpeg-utils manual\fR.
Default and minimum resolution is \f(CW\*(C`640x480\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBmeter\fR" 4
.IX Item "meter"
Set the \s-1EBU\s0 scale meter. Default is \f(CW9\fR. Common values are \f(CW9\fR and
\&\f(CW18\fR, respectively for \s-1EBU\s0 scale meter +9 and \s-1EBU\s0 scale meter +18. Any
other integer value between this range is allowed.
.IP "\fBmetadata\fR" 4
.IX Item "metadata"
Set metadata injection. If set to \f(CW1\fR, the audio input will be segmented
into 100ms output frames, each of them containing various loudness information
in metadata.  All the metadata keys are prefixed with \f(CW\*(C`lavfi.r128.\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
Default is \f(CW0\fR.
.IP "\fBframelog\fR" 4
.IX Item "framelog"
Force the frame logging level.
.Sp
Available values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBinfo\fR" 4
.IX Item "info"
information logging level
.IP "\fBverbose\fR" 4
.IX Item "verbose"
verbose logging level
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
By default, the logging level is set to \fIinfo\fR. If the \fBvideo\fR or
the \fBmetadata\fR options are set, it switches to \fIverbose\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBpeak\fR" 4
.IX Item "peak"
Set peak mode(s).
.Sp
Available modes can be cumulated (the option is a \f(CW\*(C`flag\*(C'\fR type). Possible
values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBnone\fR" 4
.IX Item "none"
Disable any peak mode (default).
.IP "\fBsample\fR" 4
.IX Item "sample"
Enable sample-peak mode.
.Sp
Simple peak mode looking for the higher sample value. It logs a message
for sample-peak (identified by \f(CW\*(C`SPK\*(C'\fR).
.IP "\fBtrue\fR" 4
.IX Item "true"
Enable true-peak mode.
.Sp
If enabled, the peak lookup is done on an over-sampled version of the input
stream for better peak accuracy. It logs a message for true-peak.
(identified by \f(CW\*(C`TPK\*(C'\fR) and true-peak per frame (identified by \f(CW\*(C`FTPK\*(C'\fR).
This mode requires a build with \f(CW\*(C`libswresample\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBdualmono\fR" 4
.IX Item "dualmono"
Treat mono input files as \*(L"dual mono\*(R". If a mono file is intended for playback
on a stereo system, its \s-1EBU R128\s0 measurement will be perceptually incorrect.
If set to \f(CW\*(C`true\*(C'\fR, this option will compensate for this effect.
Multi-channel input files are not affected by this option.
.IP "\fBpanlaw\fR" 4
.IX Item "panlaw"
Set a specific pan law to be used for the measurement of dual mono files.
This parameter is optional, and has a default value of \-3.01dB.
.IP "\fBtarget\fR" 4
.IX Item "target"
Set a specific target level (in \s-1LUFS\s0) used as relative zero in the visualization.
This parameter is optional and has a default value of \-23LUFS as specified
by \s-1EBU R128.\s0 However, material published online may prefer a level of \-16LUFS
(e.g. for use with podcasts or video platforms).
.IP "\fBgauge\fR" 4
.IX Item "gauge"
Set the value displayed by the gauge. Valid values are \f(CW\*(C`momentary\*(C'\fR and s
\&\f(CW\*(C`shortterm\*(C'\fR. By default the momentary value will be used, but in certain
scenarios it may be more useful to observe the short term value instead (e.g.
live mixing).
.IP "\fBscale\fR" 4
.IX Item "scale"
Sets the display scale for the loudness. Valid parameters are \f(CW\*(C`absolute\*(C'\fR
(in \s-1LUFS\s0) or \f(CW\*(C`relative\*(C'\fR (\s-1LU\s0) relative to the target. This only affects the
video output, not the summary or continuous log output.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Real-time graph using \fBffplay\fR, with a \s-1EBU\s0 scale meter +18:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \-i "amovie=input.mp3,ebur128=video=1:meter=18 [out0][out1]"
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Run an analysis with \fBffmpeg\fR:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-nostats \-i input.mp3 \-filter_complex ebur128 \-f null \-
.Ve
.SS "interleave, ainterleave"
.IX Subsection "interleave, ainterleave"
Temporally interleave frames from several inputs.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`interleave\*(C'\fR works with video inputs, \f(CW\*(C`ainterleave\*(C'\fR with audio.
.PP
These filters read frames from several inputs and send the oldest
queued frame to the output.
.PP
Input streams must have well defined, monotonically increasing frame
timestamp values.
.PP
In order to submit one frame to output, these filters need to enqueue
at least one frame for each input, so they cannot work in case one
input is not yet terminated and will not receive incoming frames.
.PP
For example consider the case when one input is a \f(CW\*(C`select\*(C'\fR filter
which always drops input frames. The \f(CW\*(C`interleave\*(C'\fR filter will keep
reading from that input, but it will never be able to send new frames
to output until the input sends an end-of-stream signal.
.PP
Also, depending on inputs synchronization, the filters will drop
frames in case one input receives more frames than the other ones, and
the queue is already filled.
.PP
These filters accept the following options:
.IP "\fBnb_inputs, n\fR" 4
.IX Item "nb_inputs, n"
Set the number of different inputs, it is 2 by default.
.IP "\fBduration\fR" 4
.IX Item "duration"
How to determine the end-of-stream.
.RS 4
.IP "\fBlongest\fR" 4
.IX Item "longest"
The duration of the longest input. (default)
.IP "\fBshortest\fR" 4
.IX Item "shortest"
The duration of the shortest input.
.IP "\fBfirst\fR" 4
.IX Item "first"
The duration of the first input.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Interleave frames belonging to different streams using \fBffmpeg\fR:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-i bambi.avi \-i pr0n.mkv \-filter_complex "[0:v][1:v] interleave" out.avi
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Add flickering blur effect:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=\*(Aqif(gt(random(0), 0.2), 1, 2)\*(Aq:n=2 [tmp], boxblur=2:2, [tmp] interleave
.Ve
.SS "metadata, ametadata"
.IX Subsection "metadata, ametadata"
Manipulate frame metadata.
.PP
This filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBmode\fR" 4
.IX Item "mode"
Set mode of operation of the filter.
.Sp
Can be one of the following:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBselect\fR" 4
.IX Item "select"
If both \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR is set, select frames
which have such metadata. If only \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR is set, select
every frame that has such key in metadata.
.IP "\fBadd\fR" 4
.IX Item "add"
Add new metadata \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR. If key is already available
do nothing.
.IP "\fBmodify\fR" 4
.IX Item "modify"
Modify value of already present key.
.IP "\fBdelete\fR" 4
.IX Item "delete"
If \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR is set, delete only keys that have such value.
Otherwise, delete key. If \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR is not set, delete all metadata values in
the frame.
.IP "\fBprint\fR" 4
.IX Item "print"
Print key and its value if metadata was found. If \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR is not set print all
metadata values available in frame.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBkey\fR" 4
.IX Item "key"
Set key used with all modes. Must be set for all modes except \f(CW\*(C`print\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`delete\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBvalue\fR" 4
.IX Item "value"
Set metadata value which will be used. This option is mandatory for
\&\f(CW\*(C`modify\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`add\*(C'\fR mode.
.IP "\fBfunction\fR" 4
.IX Item "function"
Which function to use when comparing metadata value and \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
Can be one of following:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBsame_str\fR" 4
.IX Item "same_str"
Values are interpreted as strings, returns true if metadata value is same as \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBstarts_with\fR" 4
.IX Item "starts_with"
Values are interpreted as strings, returns true if metadata value starts with
the \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR option string.
.IP "\fBless\fR" 4
.IX Item "less"
Values are interpreted as floats, returns true if metadata value is less than \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBequal\fR" 4
.IX Item "equal"
Values are interpreted as floats, returns true if \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR is equal with metadata value.
.IP "\fBgreater\fR" 4
.IX Item "greater"
Values are interpreted as floats, returns true if metadata value is greater than \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBexpr\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr"
Values are interpreted as floats, returns true if expression from option \f(CW\*(C`expr\*(C'\fR
evaluates to true.
.IP "\fBends_with\fR" 4
.IX Item "ends_with"
Values are interpreted as strings, returns true if metadata value ends with
the \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR option string.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBexpr\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr"
Set expression which is used when \f(CW\*(C`function\*(C'\fR is set to \f(CW\*(C`expr\*(C'\fR.
The expression is evaluated through the eval \s-1API\s0 and can contain the following
constants:
.RS 4
.IP "\fB\s-1VALUE1\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "VALUE1"
Float representation of \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR from metadata key.
.IP "\fB\s-1VALUE2\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "VALUE2"
Float representation of \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR as supplied by user in \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR option.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBfile\fR" 4
.IX Item "file"
If specified in \f(CW\*(C`print\*(C'\fR mode, output is written to the named file. Instead of
plain filename any writable url can be specified. Filename ``\-'' is a shorthand
for standard output. If \f(CW\*(C`file\*(C'\fR option is not set, output is written to the log
with \s-1AV_LOG_INFO\s0 loglevel.
.IP "\fBdirect\fR" 4
.IX Item "direct"
Reduces buffering in print mode when output is written to a \s-1URL\s0 set using \fIfile\fR.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Print all metadata values for frames with key \f(CW\*(C`lavfi.signalstats.YDIF\*(C'\fR with values
between 0 and 1.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        signalstats,metadata=print:key=lavfi.signalstats.YDIF:value=0:function=expr:expr=\*(Aqbetween(VALUE1,0,1)\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Print silencedetect output to file \fImetadata.txt\fR.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        silencedetect,ametadata=mode=print:file=metadata.txt
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Direct all metadata to a pipe with file descriptor 4.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        metadata=mode=print:file=\*(Aqpipe\e:4\*(Aq
.Ve
.SS "perms, aperms"
.IX Subsection "perms, aperms"
Set read/write permissions for the output frames.
.PP
These filters are mainly aimed at developers to test direct path in the
following filter in the filtergraph.
.PP
The filters accept the following options:
.IP "\fBmode\fR" 4
.IX Item "mode"
Select the permissions mode.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBnone\fR" 4
.IX Item "none"
Do nothing. This is the default.
.IP "\fBro\fR" 4
.IX Item "ro"
Set all the output frames read-only.
.IP "\fBrw\fR" 4
.IX Item "rw"
Set all the output frames directly writable.
.IP "\fBtoggle\fR" 4
.IX Item "toggle"
Make the frame read-only if writable, and writable if read-only.
.IP "\fBrandom\fR" 4
.IX Item "random"
Set each output frame read-only or writable randomly.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBseed\fR" 4
.IX Item "seed"
Set the seed for the \fIrandom\fR mode, must be an integer included between
\&\f(CW0\fR and \f(CW\*(C`UINT32_MAX\*(C'\fR. If not specified, or if explicitly set to
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR, the filter will try to use a good random seed on a best effort
basis.
.PP
Note: in case of auto-inserted filter between the permission filter and the
following one, the permission might not be received as expected in that
following filter. Inserting a \fBformat\fR or \fBaformat\fR filter before the
perms/aperms filter can avoid this problem.
.SS "realtime, arealtime"
.IX Subsection "realtime, arealtime"
Slow down filtering to match real time approximately.
.PP
These filters will pause the filtering for a variable amount of time to
match the output rate with the input timestamps.
They are similar to the \fBre\fR option to \f(CW\*(C`ffmpeg\*(C'\fR.
.PP
They accept the following options:
.IP "\fBlimit\fR" 4
.IX Item "limit"
Time limit for the pauses. Any pause longer than that will be considered
a timestamp discontinuity and reset the timer. Default is 2 seconds.
.IP "\fBspeed\fR" 4
.IX Item "speed"
Speed factor for processing. The value must be a float larger than zero.
Values larger than 1.0 will result in faster than realtime processing,
smaller will slow processing down. The \fIlimit\fR is automatically adapted
accordingly. Default is 1.0.
.Sp
A processing speed faster than what is possible without these filters cannot
be achieved.
.SS "select, aselect"
.IX Subsection "select, aselect"
Select frames to pass in output.
.PP
This filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBexpr, e\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr, e"
Set expression, which is evaluated for each input frame.
.Sp
If the expression is evaluated to zero, the frame is discarded.
.Sp
If the evaluation result is negative or NaN, the frame is sent to the
first output; otherwise it is sent to the output with index
\&\f(CW\*(C`ceil(val)\-1\*(C'\fR, assuming that the input index starts from 0.
.Sp
For example a value of \f(CW1.2\fR corresponds to the output with index
\&\f(CW\*(C`ceil(1.2)\-1 = 2\-1 = 1\*(C'\fR, that is the second output.
.IP "\fBoutputs, n\fR" 4
.IX Item "outputs, n"
Set the number of outputs. The output to which to send the selected
frame is based on the result of the evaluation. Default value is 1.
.PP
The expression can contain the following constants:
.IP "\fBn\fR" 4
.IX Item "n"
The (sequential) number of the filtered frame, starting from 0.
.IP "\fBselected_n\fR" 4
.IX Item "selected_n"
The (sequential) number of the selected frame, starting from 0.
.IP "\fBprev_selected_n\fR" 4
.IX Item "prev_selected_n"
The sequential number of the last selected frame. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fB\s-1TB\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TB"
The timebase of the input timestamps.
.IP "\fBpts\fR" 4
.IX Item "pts"
The \s-1PTS\s0 (Presentation TimeStamp) of the filtered video frame,
expressed in \fI\s-1TB\s0\fR units. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBt\fR" 4
.IX Item "t"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the filtered video frame,
expressed in seconds. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBprev_pts\fR" 4
.IX Item "prev_pts"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the previously filtered video frame. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBprev_selected_pts\fR" 4
.IX Item "prev_selected_pts"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the last previously filtered video frame. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBprev_selected_t\fR" 4
.IX Item "prev_selected_t"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the last previously selected video frame, expressed in seconds. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBstart_pts\fR" 4
.IX Item "start_pts"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the first video frame in the video. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBstart_t\fR" 4
.IX Item "start_t"
The time of the first video frame in the video. It's \s-1NAN\s0 if undefined.
.IP "\fBpict_type\fR \fI(video only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "pict_type (video only)"
The type of the filtered frame. It can assume one of the following
values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBI\fR" 4
.IX Item "I"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBP\fR" 4
.IX Item "P"
.IP "\fBB\fR" 4
.IX Item "B"
.IP "\fBS\fR" 4
.IX Item "S"
.IP "\fB\s-1SI\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "SI"
.IP "\fB\s-1SP\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "SP"
.IP "\fB\s-1BI\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "BI"
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBinterlace_type\fR \fI(video only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "interlace_type (video only)"
.PD
The frame interlace type. It can assume one of the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fB\s-1PROGRESSIVE\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PROGRESSIVE"
The frame is progressive (not interlaced).
.IP "\fB\s-1TOPFIRST\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TOPFIRST"
The frame is top-field-first.
.IP "\fB\s-1BOTTOMFIRST\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "BOTTOMFIRST"
The frame is bottom-field-first.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBconsumed_sample_n\fR \fI(audio only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "consumed_sample_n (audio only)"
the number of selected samples before the current frame
.IP "\fBsamples_n\fR \fI(audio only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "samples_n (audio only)"
the number of samples in the current frame
.IP "\fBsample_rate\fR \fI(audio only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "sample_rate (audio only)"
the input sample rate
.IP "\fBkey\fR" 4
.IX Item "key"
This is 1 if the filtered frame is a key-frame, 0 otherwise.
.IP "\fBpos\fR" 4
.IX Item "pos"
the position in the file of the filtered frame, \-1 if the information
is not available (e.g. for synthetic video)
.IP "\fBscene\fR \fI(video only)\fR" 4
.IX Item "scene (video only)"
value between 0 and 1 to indicate a new scene; a low value reflects a low
probability for the current frame to introduce a new scene, while a higher
value means the current frame is more likely to be one (see the example below)
.IP "\fBconcatdec_select\fR" 4
.IX Item "concatdec_select"
The concat demuxer can select only part of a concat input file by setting an
inpoint and an outpoint, but the output packets may not be entirely contained
in the selected interval. By using this variable, it is possible to skip frames
generated by the concat demuxer which are not exactly contained in the selected
interval.
.Sp
This works by comparing the frame pts against the \fIlavf.concat.start_time\fR
and the \fIlavf.concat.duration\fR packet metadata values which are also
present in the decoded frames.
.Sp
The \fIconcatdec_select\fR variable is \-1 if the frame pts is at least
start_time and either the duration metadata is missing or the frame pts is less
than start_time + duration, 0 otherwise, and NaN if the start_time metadata is
missing.
.Sp
That basically means that an input frame is selected if its pts is within the
interval set by the concat demuxer.
.PP
The default value of the select expression is \*(L"1\*(R".
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select all frames in input:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select
.Ve
.Sp
The example above is the same as:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=1
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Skip all frames:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=0
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select only I\-frames:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=\*(Aqeq(pict_type\e,I)\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select one frame every 100:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=\*(Aqnot(mod(n\e,100))\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select only frames contained in the 10\-20 time interval:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=between(t\e,10\e,20)
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select only I\-frames contained in the 10\-20 time interval:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=between(t\e,10\e,20)*eq(pict_type\e,I)
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select frames with a minimum distance of 10 seconds:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=\*(Aqisnan(prev_selected_t)+gte(t\-prev_selected_t\e,10)\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Use aselect to select only audio frames with samples number > 100:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        aselect=\*(Aqgt(samples_n\e,100)\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Create a mosaic of the first scenes:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-i video.avi \-vf select=\*(Aqgt(scene\e,0.4)\*(Aq,scale=160:120,tile \-frames:v 1 preview.png
.Ve
.Sp
Comparing \fIscene\fR against a value between 0.3 and 0.5 is generally a sane
choice.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Send even and odd frames to separate outputs, and compose them:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        select=n=2:e=\*(Aqmod(n, 2)+1\*(Aq [odd][even]; [odd] pad=h=2*ih [tmp]; [tmp][even] overlay=y=h
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Select useful frames from an ffconcat file which is using inpoints and
outpoints but where the source files are not intra frame only.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffmpeg \-copyts \-vsync 0 \-segment_time_metadata 1 \-i input.ffconcat \-vf select=concatdec_select \-af aselect=concatdec_select output.avi
.Ve
.SS "sendcmd, asendcmd"
.IX Subsection "sendcmd, asendcmd"
Send commands to filters in the filtergraph.
.PP
These filters read commands to be sent to other filters in the
filtergraph.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`sendcmd\*(C'\fR must be inserted between two video filters,
\&\f(CW\*(C`asendcmd\*(C'\fR must be inserted between two audio filters, but apart
from that they act the same way.
.PP
The specification of commands can be provided in the filter arguments
with the \fIcommands\fR option, or in a file specified by the
\&\fIfilename\fR option.
.PP
These filters accept the following options:
.IP "\fBcommands, c\fR" 4
.IX Item "commands, c"
Set the commands to be read and sent to the other filters.
.IP "\fBfilename, f\fR" 4
.IX Item "filename, f"
Set the filename of the commands to be read and sent to the other
filters.
.PP
\fICommands syntax\fR
.IX Subsection "Commands syntax"
.PP
A commands description consists of a sequence of interval
specifications, comprising a list of commands to be executed when a
particular event related to that interval occurs. The occurring event
is typically the current frame time entering or leaving a given time
interval.
.PP
An interval is specified by the following syntax:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        <START>[\-<END>] <COMMANDS>;
.Ve
.PP
The time interval is specified by the \fI\s-1START\s0\fR and \fI\s-1END\s0\fR times.
\&\fI\s-1END\s0\fR is optional and defaults to the maximum time.
.PP
The current frame time is considered within the specified interval if
it is included in the interval [\fI\s-1START\s0\fR, \fI\s-1END\s0\fR), that is when
the time is greater or equal to \fI\s-1START\s0\fR and is lesser than
\&\fI\s-1END\s0\fR.
.PP
\&\fI\s-1COMMANDS\s0\fR consists of a sequence of one or more command
specifications, separated by \*(L",\*(R", relating to that interval.  The
syntax of a command specification is given by:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        [<FLAGS>] <TARGET> <COMMAND> <ARG>
.Ve
.PP
\&\fI\s-1FLAGS\s0\fR is optional and specifies the type of events relating to
the time interval which enable sending the specified command, and must
be a non-null sequence of identifier flags separated by \*(L"+\*(R" or \*(L"|\*(R" and
enclosed between \*(L"[\*(R" and \*(L"]\*(R".
.PP
The following flags are recognized:
.IP "\fBenter\fR" 4
.IX Item "enter"
The command is sent when the current frame timestamp enters the
specified interval. In other words, the command is sent when the
previous frame timestamp was not in the given interval, and the
current is.
.IP "\fBleave\fR" 4
.IX Item "leave"
The command is sent when the current frame timestamp leaves the
specified interval. In other words, the command is sent when the
previous frame timestamp was in the given interval, and the
current is not.
.IP "\fBexpr\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr"
The command \fI\s-1ARG\s0\fR is interpreted as expression and result of
expression is passed as \fI\s-1ARG\s0\fR.
.Sp
The expression is evaluated through the eval \s-1API\s0 and can contain the following
constants:
.RS 4
.IP "\fB\s-1POS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "POS"
Original position in the file of the frame, or undefined if undefined
for the current frame.
.IP "\fB\s-1PTS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PTS"
The presentation timestamp in input.
.IP "\fBN\fR" 4
.IX Item "N"
The count of the input frame for video or audio, starting from 0.
.IP "\fBT\fR" 4
.IX Item "T"
The time in seconds of the current frame.
.IP "\fB\s-1TS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TS"
The start time in seconds of the current command interval.
.IP "\fB\s-1TE\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TE"
The end time in seconds of the current command interval.
.IP "\fB\s-1TI\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TI"
The interpolated time of the current command interval, \s-1TI\s0 = (T \- \s-1TS\s0) / (\s-1TE\s0 \- \s-1TS\s0).
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.PP
If \fI\s-1FLAGS\s0\fR is not specified, a default value of \f(CW\*(C`[enter]\*(C'\fR is
assumed.
.PP
\&\fI\s-1TARGET\s0\fR specifies the target of the command, usually the name of
the filter class or a specific filter instance name.
.PP
\&\fI\s-1COMMAND\s0\fR specifies the name of the command for the target filter.
.PP
\&\fI\s-1ARG\s0\fR is optional and specifies the optional list of argument for
the given \fI\s-1COMMAND\s0\fR.
.PP
Between one interval specification and another, whitespaces, or
sequences of characters starting with \f(CW\*(C`#\*(C'\fR until the end of line,
are ignored and can be used to annotate comments.
.PP
A simplified \s-1BNF\s0 description of the commands specification syntax
follows:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&        <COMMAND_FLAG>  ::= "enter" | "leave"
\&        <COMMAND_FLAGS> ::= <COMMAND_FLAG> [(+|"|")<COMMAND_FLAG>]
\&        <COMMAND>       ::= ["[" <COMMAND_FLAGS> "]"] <TARGET> <COMMAND> [<ARG>]
\&        <COMMANDS>      ::= <COMMAND> [,<COMMANDS>]
\&        <INTERVAL>      ::= <START>[\-<END>] <COMMANDS>
\&        <INTERVALS>     ::= <INTERVAL>[;<INTERVALS>]
.Ve
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Specify audio tempo change at second 4:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        asendcmd=c=\*(Aq4.0 atempo tempo 1.5\*(Aq,atempo
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Target a specific filter instance:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        asendcmd=c=\*(Aq4.0 atempo@my tempo 1.5\*(Aq,atempo@my
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Specify a list of drawtext and hue commands in a file.
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        # show text in the interval 5\-10
\&        5.0\-10.0 [enter] drawtext reinit \*(Aqfontfile=FreeSerif.ttf:text=hello world\*(Aq,
\&                 [leave] drawtext reinit \*(Aqfontfile=FreeSerif.ttf:text=\*(Aq;
\&        
\&        # desaturate the image in the interval 15\-20
\&        15.0\-20.0 [enter] hue s 0,
\&                  [enter] drawtext reinit \*(Aqfontfile=FreeSerif.ttf:text=nocolor\*(Aq,
\&                  [leave] hue s 1,
\&                  [leave] drawtext reinit \*(Aqfontfile=FreeSerif.ttf:text=color\*(Aq;
\&        
\&        # apply an exponential saturation fade\-out effect, starting from time 25
\&        25 [enter] hue s exp(25\-t)
.Ve
.Sp
A filtergraph allowing to read and process the above command list
stored in a file \fItest.cmd\fR, can be specified with:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        sendcmd=f=test.cmd,drawtext=fontfile=FreeSerif.ttf:text=\*(Aq\*(Aq,hue
.Ve
.SS "setpts, asetpts"
.IX Subsection "setpts, asetpts"
Change the \s-1PTS\s0 (presentation timestamp) of the input frames.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`setpts\*(C'\fR works on video frames, \f(CW\*(C`asetpts\*(C'\fR on audio frames.
.PP
This filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBexpr\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr"
The expression which is evaluated for each frame to construct its timestamp.
.PP
The expression is evaluated through the eval \s-1API\s0 and can contain the following
constants:
.IP "\fB\s-1FRAME_RATE, FR\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "FRAME_RATE, FR"
frame rate, only defined for constant frame-rate video
.IP "\fB\s-1PTS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PTS"
The presentation timestamp in input
.IP "\fBN\fR" 4
.IX Item "N"
The count of the input frame for video or the number of consumed samples,
not including the current frame for audio, starting from 0.
.IP "\fB\s-1NB_CONSUMED_SAMPLES\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "NB_CONSUMED_SAMPLES"
The number of consumed samples, not including the current frame (only
audio)
.IP "\fB\s-1NB_SAMPLES, S\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "NB_SAMPLES, S"
The number of samples in the current frame (only audio)
.IP "\fB\s-1SAMPLE_RATE, SR\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "SAMPLE_RATE, SR"
The audio sample rate.
.IP "\fB\s-1STARTPTS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "STARTPTS"
The \s-1PTS\s0 of the first frame.
.IP "\fB\s-1STARTT\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "STARTT"
the time in seconds of the first frame
.IP "\fB\s-1INTERLACED\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "INTERLACED"
State whether the current frame is interlaced.
.IP "\fBT\fR" 4
.IX Item "T"
the time in seconds of the current frame
.IP "\fB\s-1POS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "POS"
original position in the file of the frame, or undefined if undefined
for the current frame
.IP "\fB\s-1PREV_INPTS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PREV_INPTS"
The previous input \s-1PTS.\s0
.IP "\fB\s-1PREV_INT\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PREV_INT"
previous input time in seconds
.IP "\fB\s-1PREV_OUTPTS\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PREV_OUTPTS"
The previous output \s-1PTS.\s0
.IP "\fB\s-1PREV_OUTT\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "PREV_OUTT"
previous output time in seconds
.IP "\fB\s-1RTCTIME\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "RTCTIME"
The wallclock (\s-1RTC\s0) time in microseconds. This is deprecated, use \fBtime\fR\|(0)
instead.
.IP "\fB\s-1RTCSTART\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "RTCSTART"
The wallclock (\s-1RTC\s0) time at the start of the movie in microseconds.
.IP "\fB\s-1TB\s0\fR" 4
.IX Item "TB"
The timebase of the input timestamps.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Start counting \s-1PTS\s0 from zero
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=PTS\-STARTPTS
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply fast motion effect:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=0.5*PTS
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply slow motion effect:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=2.0*PTS
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set fixed rate of 25 frames per second:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=N/(25*TB)
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set fixed rate 25 fps with some jitter:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=\*(Aq1/(25*TB) * (N + 0.05 * sin(N*2*PI/25))\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Apply an offset of 10 seconds to the input \s-1PTS:\s0
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=PTS+10/TB
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Generate timestamps from a \*(L"live source\*(R" and rebase onto the current timebase:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        setpts=\*(Aq(RTCTIME \- RTCSTART) / (TB * 1000000)\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Generate timestamps by counting samples:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        asetpts=N/SR/TB
.Ve
.SS "setrange"
.IX Subsection "setrange"
Force color range for the output video frame.
.PP
The \f(CW\*(C`setrange\*(C'\fR filter marks the color range property for the
output frames. It does not change the input frame, but only sets the
corresponding property, which affects how the frame is treated by
following filters.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBrange\fR" 4
.IX Item "range"
Available values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBauto\fR" 4
.IX Item "auto"
Keep the same color range property.
.IP "\fBunspecified, unknown\fR" 4
.IX Item "unspecified, unknown"
Set the color range as unspecified.
.IP "\fBlimited, tv, mpeg\fR" 4
.IX Item "limited, tv, mpeg"
Set the color range as limited.
.IP "\fBfull, pc, jpeg\fR" 4
.IX Item "full, pc, jpeg"
Set the color range as full.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.SS "settb, asettb"
.IX Subsection "settb, asettb"
Set the timebase to use for the output frames timestamps.
It is mainly useful for testing timebase configuration.
.PP
It accepts the following parameters:
.IP "\fBexpr, tb\fR" 4
.IX Item "expr, tb"
The expression which is evaluated into the output timebase.
.PP
The value for \fBtb\fR is an arithmetic expression representing a
rational. The expression can contain the constants \*(L"\s-1AVTB\*(R"\s0 (the default
timebase), \*(L"intb\*(R" (the input timebase) and \*(L"sr\*(R" (the sample rate,
audio only). Default value is \*(L"intb\*(R".
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set the timebase to 1/25:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        settb=expr=1/25
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set the timebase to 1/10:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        settb=expr=0.1
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set the timebase to 1001/1000:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        settb=1+0.001
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set the timebase to 2*intb:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        settb=2*intb
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Set the default timebase value:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        settb=AVTB
.Ve
.SS "showcqt"
.IX Subsection "showcqt"
Convert input audio to a video output representing frequency spectrum
logarithmically using Brown-Puckette constant Q transform algorithm with
direct frequency domain coefficient calculation (but the transform itself
is not really constant Q, instead the Q factor is actually variable/clamped),
with musical tone scale, from E0 to D#10.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBsize, s\fR" 4
.IX Item "size, s"
Specify the video size for the output. It must be even. For the syntax of this option,
check the \fB\*(L"Video size\*(R" section in the ffmpeg-utils manual\fR.
Default value is \f(CW\*(C`1920x1080\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBfps, rate, r\fR" 4
.IX Item "fps, rate, r"
Set the output frame rate. Default value is \f(CW25\fR.
.IP "\fBbar_h\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar_h"
Set the bargraph height. It must be even. Default value is \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR which
computes the bargraph height automatically.
.IP "\fBaxis_h\fR" 4
.IX Item "axis_h"
Set the axis height. It must be even. Default value is \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR which computes
the axis height automatically.
.IP "\fBsono_h\fR" 4
.IX Item "sono_h"
Set the sonogram height. It must be even. Default value is \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR which
computes the sonogram height automatically.
.IP "\fBfullhd\fR" 4
.IX Item "fullhd"
Set the fullhd resolution. This option is deprecated, use \fIsize\fR, \fIs\fR
instead. Default value is \f(CW1\fR.
.IP "\fBsono_v, volume\fR" 4
.IX Item "sono_v, volume"
Specify the sonogram volume expression. It can contain variables:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBbar_v\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar_v"
the \fIbar_v\fR evaluated expression
.IP "\fBfrequency, freq, f\fR" 4
.IX Item "frequency, freq, f"
the frequency where it is evaluated
.IP "\fBtimeclamp, tc\fR" 4
.IX Item "timeclamp, tc"
the value of \fItimeclamp\fR option
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
and functions:
.IP "\fBa_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "a_weighting(f)"
A\-weighting of equal loudness
.IP "\fBb_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "b_weighting(f)"
B\-weighting of equal loudness
.IP "\fBc_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "c_weighting(f)"
C\-weighting of equal loudness.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default value is \f(CW16\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBbar_v, volume2\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar_v, volume2"
Specify the bargraph volume expression. It can contain variables:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBsono_v\fR" 4
.IX Item "sono_v"
the \fIsono_v\fR evaluated expression
.IP "\fBfrequency, freq, f\fR" 4
.IX Item "frequency, freq, f"
the frequency where it is evaluated
.IP "\fBtimeclamp, tc\fR" 4
.IX Item "timeclamp, tc"
the value of \fItimeclamp\fR option
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
and functions:
.IP "\fBa_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "a_weighting(f)"
A\-weighting of equal loudness
.IP "\fBb_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "b_weighting(f)"
B\-weighting of equal loudness
.IP "\fBc_weighting(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "c_weighting(f)"
C\-weighting of equal loudness.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default value is \f(CW\*(C`sono_v\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBsono_g, gamma\fR" 4
.IX Item "sono_g, gamma"
Specify the sonogram gamma. Lower gamma makes the spectrum more contrast,
higher gamma makes the spectrum having more range. Default value is \f(CW3\fR.
Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 7]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBbar_g, gamma2\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar_g, gamma2"
Specify the bargraph gamma. Default value is \f(CW1\fR. Acceptable range is
\&\f(CW\*(C`[1, 7]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBbar_t\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar_t"
Specify the bargraph transparency level. Lower value makes the bargraph sharper.
Default value is \f(CW1\fR. Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[0, 1]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBtimeclamp, tc\fR" 4
.IX Item "timeclamp, tc"
Specify the transform timeclamp. At low frequency, there is trade-off between
accuracy in time domain and frequency domain. If timeclamp is lower,
event in time domain is represented more accurately (such as fast bass drum),
otherwise event in frequency domain is represented more accurately
(such as bass guitar). Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[0.002, 1]\*(C'\fR. Default value is \f(CW0.17\fR.
.IP "\fBattack\fR" 4
.IX Item "attack"
Set attack time in seconds. The default is \f(CW0\fR (disabled). Otherwise, it
limits future samples by applying asymmetric windowing in time domain, useful
when low latency is required. Accepted range is \f(CW\*(C`[0, 1]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBbasefreq\fR" 4
.IX Item "basefreq"
Specify the transform base frequency. Default value is \f(CW20.01523126408007475\fR,
which is frequency 50 cents below E0. Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[10, 100000]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBendfreq\fR" 4
.IX Item "endfreq"
Specify the transform end frequency. Default value is \f(CW20495.59681441799654\fR,
which is frequency 50 cents above D#10. Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[10, 100000]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBcoeffclamp\fR" 4
.IX Item "coeffclamp"
This option is deprecated and ignored.
.IP "\fBtlength\fR" 4
.IX Item "tlength"
Specify the transform length in time domain. Use this option to control accuracy
trade-off between time domain and frequency domain at every frequency sample.
It can contain variables:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBfrequency, freq, f\fR" 4
.IX Item "frequency, freq, f"
the frequency where it is evaluated
.IP "\fBtimeclamp, tc\fR" 4
.IX Item "timeclamp, tc"
the value of \fItimeclamp\fR option.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default value is \f(CW\*(C`384*tc/(384+tc*f)\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBcount\fR" 4
.IX Item "count"
Specify the transform count for every video frame. Default value is \f(CW6\fR.
Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[1, 30]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBfcount\fR" 4
.IX Item "fcount"
Specify the transform count for every single pixel. Default value is \f(CW0\fR,
which makes it computed automatically. Acceptable range is \f(CW\*(C`[0, 10]\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBfontfile\fR" 4
.IX Item "fontfile"
Specify font file for use with freetype to draw the axis. If not specified,
use embedded font. Note that drawing with font file or embedded font is not
implemented with custom \fIbasefreq\fR and \fIendfreq\fR, use \fIaxisfile\fR
option instead.
.IP "\fBfont\fR" 4
.IX Item "font"
Specify fontconfig pattern. This has lower priority than \fIfontfile\fR. The
\&\f(CW\*(C`:\*(C'\fR in the pattern may be replaced by \f(CW\*(C`|\*(C'\fR to avoid unnecessary
escaping.
.IP "\fBfontcolor\fR" 4
.IX Item "fontcolor"
Specify font color expression. This is arithmetic expression that should return
integer value 0xRRGGBB. It can contain variables:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBfrequency, freq, f\fR" 4
.IX Item "frequency, freq, f"
the frequency where it is evaluated
.IP "\fBtimeclamp, tc\fR" 4
.IX Item "timeclamp, tc"
the value of \fItimeclamp\fR option
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
and functions:
.IP "\fBmidi(f)\fR" 4
.IX Item "midi(f)"
midi number of frequency f, some midi numbers: E0(16), C1(24), C2(36), A4(69)
.IP "\fBr(x), g(x), b(x)\fR" 4
.IX Item "r(x), g(x), b(x)"
red, green, and blue value of intensity x.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default value is \f(CW\*(C`st(0, (midi(f)\-59.5)/12);
st(1, if(between(ld(0),0,1), 0.5\-0.5*cos(2*PI*ld(0)), 0));
r(1\-ld(1)) + b(ld(1))\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBaxisfile\fR" 4
.IX Item "axisfile"
Specify image file to draw the axis. This option override \fIfontfile\fR and
\&\fIfontcolor\fR option.
.IP "\fBaxis, text\fR" 4
.IX Item "axis, text"
Enable/disable drawing text to the axis. If it is set to \f(CW0\fR, drawing to
the axis is disabled, ignoring \fIfontfile\fR and \fIaxisfile\fR option.
Default value is \f(CW1\fR.
.IP "\fBcsp\fR" 4
.IX Item "csp"
Set colorspace. The accepted values are:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBunspecified\fR" 4
.IX Item "unspecified"
Unspecified (default)
.IP "\fBbt709\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt709"
\&\s-1BT.709\s0
.IP "\fBfcc\fR" 4
.IX Item "fcc"
\&\s-1FCC\s0
.IP "\fBbt470bg\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt470bg"
\&\s-1BT.470BG\s0 or \s-1BT.601\-6 625\s0
.IP "\fBsmpte170m\fR" 4
.IX Item "smpte170m"
\&\s-1SMPTE\-170M\s0 or \s-1BT.601\-6 525\s0
.IP "\fBsmpte240m\fR" 4
.IX Item "smpte240m"
\&\s-1SMPTE\-240M\s0
.IP "\fBbt2020ncl\fR" 4
.IX Item "bt2020ncl"
\&\s-1BT.2020\s0 with non-constant luminance
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.IP "\fBcscheme\fR" 4
.IX Item "cscheme"
Set spectrogram color scheme. This is list of floating point values with format
\&\f(CW\*(C`left_r|left_g|left_b|right_r|right_g|right_b\*(C'\fR.
The default is \f(CW\*(C`1|0.5|0|0|0.5|1\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIExamples\fR
.IX Subsection "Examples"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Playing audio while showing the spectrum:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \*(Aqamovie=a.mp3, asplit [a][out1]; [a] showcqt [out0]\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Same as above, but with frame rate 30 fps:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \*(Aqamovie=a.mp3, asplit [a][out1]; [a] showcqt=fps=30:count=5 [out0]\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Playing at 1280x720:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \*(Aqamovie=a.mp3, asplit [a][out1]; [a] showcqt=s=1280x720:count=4 [out0]\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Disable sonogram display:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        sono_h=0
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
A1 and its harmonics: A1, A2, (near)E3, A3:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \*(Aqaevalsrc=0.1*sin(2*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(4*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(6*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(8*PI*55*t),
\&                         asplit[a][out1]; [a] showcqt [out0]\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Same as above, but with more accuracy in frequency domain:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&        ffplay \-f lavfi \*(Aqaevalsrc=0.1*sin(2*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(4*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(6*PI*55*t)+0.1*sin(8*PI*55*t),
\&                         asplit[a][out1]; [a] showcqt=timeclamp=0.5 [out0]\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom volume:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        bar_v=10:sono_v=bar_v*a_weighting(f)
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom gamma, now spectrum is linear to the amplitude.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        bar_g=2:sono_g=2
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom tlength equation:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        tc=0.33:tlength=\*(Aqst(0,0.17); 384*tc / (384 / ld(0) + tc*f /(1\-ld(0))) + 384*tc / (tc*f / ld(0) + 384 /(1\-ld(0)))\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom fontcolor and fontfile, C\-note is colored green, others are colored blue:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        fontcolor=\*(Aqif(mod(floor(midi(f)+0.5),12), 0x0000FF, g(1))\*(Aq:fontfile=myfont.ttf
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom font using fontconfig:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        font=\*(AqCourier New,Monospace,mono|bold\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
Custom frequency range with custom axis using image file:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&        axisfile=myaxis.png:basefreq=40:endfreq=10000
.Ve
.SS "showfreqs"
.IX Subsection "showfreqs"
Convert input audio to video output representing the audio power spectrum.
Audio amplitude is on Y\-axis while frequency is on X\-axis.
.PP
The filter accepts the following options:
.IP "\fBsize, s\fR" 4
.IX Item "size, s"
Specify size of video. For the syntax of this option, check the
\&\fB\*(L"Video size\*(R" section in the ffmpeg-utils manual\fR.
Default is \f(CW\*(C`1024x512\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fBmode\fR" 4
.IX Item "mode"
Set display mode.
This set how each frequency bin will be represented.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBline\fR" 4
.IX Item "line"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBbar\fR" 4
.IX Item "bar"
.IP "\fBdot\fR" 4
.IX Item "dot"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`bar\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBascale\fR" 4
.IX Item "ascale"
Set amplitude scale.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBlin\fR" 4
.IX Item "lin"
Linear scale.
.IP "\fBsqrt\fR" 4
.IX Item "sqrt"
Square root scale.
.IP "\fBcbrt\fR" 4
.IX Item "cbrt"
Cubic root scale.
.IP "\fBlog\fR" 4
.IX Item "log"
Logarithmic scale.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`log\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBfscale\fR" 4
.IX Item "fscale"
Set frequency scale.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBlin\fR" 4
.IX Item "lin"
Linear scale.
.IP "\fBlog\fR" 4
.IX Item "log"
Logarithmic scale.
.IP "\fBrlog\fR" 4
.IX Item "rlog"
Reverse logarithmic scale.
.RE
.RS 4
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`lin\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBwin_size\fR" 4
.IX Item "win_size"
Set window size. Allowed range is from 16 to 65536.
.Sp
Default is \f(CW2048\fR
.IP "\fBwin_func\fR" 4
.IX Item "win_func"
Set windowing function.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBrect\fR" 4
.IX Item "rect"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBbartlett\fR" 4
.IX Item "bartlett"
.IP "\fBhanning\fR" 4
.IX Item "hanning"
.IP "\fBhamming\fR" 4
.IX Item "hamming"
.IP "\fBblackman\fR" 4
.IX Item "blackman"
.IP "\fBwelch\fR" 4
.IX Item "welch"
.IP "\fBflattop\fR" 4
.IX Item "flattop"
.IP "\fBbharris\fR" 4
.IX Item "bharris"
.IP "\fBbnuttall\fR" 4
.IX Item "bnuttall"
.IP "\fBbhann\fR" 4
.IX Item "bhann"
.IP "\fBsine\fR" 4
.IX Item "sine"
.IP "\fBnuttall\fR" 4
.IX Item "nuttall"
.IP "\fBlanczos\fR" 4
.IX Item "lanczos"
.IP "\fBgauss\fR" 4
.IX Item "gauss"
.IP "\fBtukey\fR" 4
.IX Item "tukey"
.IP "\fBdolph\fR" 4
.IX Item "dolph"
.IP "\fBcauchy\fR" 4
.IX Item "cauchy"
.IP "\fBparzen\fR" 4
.IX Item "parzen"
.IP "\fBpoisson\fR" 4
.IX Item "poisson"
.IP "\fBbohman\fR" 4
.IX Item "bohman"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`hanning\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBoverlap\fR" 4
.IX Item "overlap"
Set window overlap. In range \f(CW\*(C`[0, 1]\*(C'\fR. Default is \f(CW1\fR,
which means optimal overlap for selected window function will be picked.
.IP "\fBaveraging\fR" 4
.IX Item "averaging"
Set time averaging. Setting this to 0 will display current maximal peaks.
Default is \f(CW1\fR, which means time averaging is disabled.
.IP "\fBcolors\fR" 4
.IX Item "colors"
Specify list of colors separated by space or by '|' which will be used to
draw channel frequencies. Unrecognized or missing colors will be replaced
by white color.
.IP "\fBcmode\fR" 4
.IX Item "cmode"
Set channel display mode.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBcombined\fR" 4
.IX Item "combined"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBseparate\fR" 4
.IX Item "separate"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`combined\*(C'\fR.
.RE
.IP "\fBminamp\fR" 4
.IX Item "minamp"
Set minimum amplitude used in \f(CW\*(C`log\*(C'\fR amplitude scaler.
.IP "\fBdata\fR" 4
.IX Item "data"
Set data display mode.
.Sp
It accepts the following values:
.RS 4
.IP "\fBmagnitude\fR" 4
.IX Item "magnitude"
.PD 0
.IP "\fBphase\fR" 4
.IX Item "phase"
.IP "\fBdelay\fR" 4
.IX Item "delay"
.RE
.RS 4
.PD
.Sp
Default is \f(CW\*(C`magnitude\*(C'\fR.
.RE
